{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QjttCGzyRUVehyYv6tR4mM","type":"tool_result","content":"apiVersion: v1\nitems:\n- apiVersion: v1\n  data:\n    plan.md: |\n      # Ray Cluster Change/Migration Plan\n      Generated: 2026-06-24\n      Namespace: ray\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 1. Current State\n\n      ### Deployments\n\n      | Resource    | Replicas | Image                  |\n      |-------------|----------|------------------------|\n      | ray-head    | 1        | rayproject/ray:2.9.0   |\n      | ray-worker  | 3        | rayproject/ray:2.9.0   |\n\n      **Non-default configuration already in place (applied prior to this plan):**\n      - ray-worker replica count raised to 3 (default is 1).\n      - ray-head image upgraded to rayproject/ray:2.9.0.\n      - ray-head Service exposes the Ray Dashboard on port 8265 (not present in a vanilla deploy).\n\n      ### Resource Requests / Limits\n\n      Neither ray-head nor ray-worker have any CPU or memory requests or limits defined\n      (`resources: {}`). The head node is configured with `--num-cpus=0` (no task\n      scheduling on head); each worker is configured with `--num-cpus=1`.\n\n      ### ray-head Service\n\n      ```\n      Name:      ray-head\n      Type:      ClusterIP\n      ClusterIP: 10.96.112.176\n      Ports:\n        gcs        6379/TCP   (Ray GCS / node connect endpoint)\n        dashboard  8265/TCP   (Ray Dashboard — exposed, ClusterIP only)\n      ```\n\n      The dashboard port (8265) is reachable inside the cluster but is NOT exposed\n      externally (no NodePort / LoadBalancer / Ingress).\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 2. Proposed Changes for the Next Upgrade Window\n\n      ### 2a. Image Upgrade: 2.9.0 → 2.10.0\n\n      Ray 2.10.0 is the next stable release and brings runtime-env improvements,\n      improved scheduling observability, and GCS HA fixes relevant to this cluster.\n      Both head and worker must be updated together to keep the protocol version in sync.\n\n      ### 2b. Add Resource Requests and Limits\n\n      Running without resource bounds risks node OOM evictions and noisy-neighbour\n      CPU contention. The values below are conservative starting points; tune after\n      one week of Prometheus data.\n\n      | Container   | CPU Request | CPU Limit | Memory Request | Memory Limit |\n      |-------------|-------------|-----------|----------------|--------------|\n      | ray-head    | 500m        | 1000m     | 1Gi            | 2Gi          |\n      | ray-worker  | 500m        | 2000m     | 1Gi            | 4Gi          |\n\n      ### 2c. Scale ray-worker to 5 Replicas\n\n      Current load tests show the 3-worker cluster saturating at peak. Scaling to 5\n      workers provides ~65 % headroom and keeps p99 task latency below the 2 s SLO.\n\n      ### 2d. Expose Dashboard via NodePort (optional, gated on security review)\n\n      The dashboard is already wired into the Service on port 8265 (ClusterIP). If the\n      team approves, switching the Service type to NodePort makes it directly reachable\n      for operators without kubectl port-forward, at the cost of a fixed host port.\n      This change is marked optional and should not be applied without a sign-off.\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 3. Exact kubectl Commands (DO NOT RUN — for review only)\n\n      ### 3a. Upgrade images to Ray 2.10.0\n\n      ```bash\n      # Upgrade ray-head image\n      kubectl -n ray set image deployment/ray-head \\\n        ray-head=rayproject/ray:2.10.0\n\n      # Upgrade ray-worker image\n      kubectl -n ray set image deployment/ray-worker \\\n        ray-worker=rayproject/ray:2.10.0\n\n      # Wait for rollouts\n      kubectl -n ray rollout status deployment/ray-head\n      kubectl -n ray rollout status deployment/ray-worker\n      ```\n\n      ### 3b. Apply resource requests and limits\n\n      ```bash\n      # ray-head resources\n      kubectl -n ray patch deployment ray-head --type=json -p='[\n        {\n          \"op\": \"add\",\n          \"path\": \"/spec/template/spec/containers/0/resources\",\n          \"value\": {\n            \"requests\": {\"cpu\": \"500m\", \"memory\": \"1Gi\"},\n            \"limits\":   {\"cpu\": \"1000m\", \"memory\": \"2Gi\"}\n          }\n        }\n      ]'\n\n      # ray-worker resources\n      kubectl -n ray patch deployment ray-worker --type=json -p='[\n        {\n          \"op\": \"add\",\n          \"path\": \"/spec/template/spec/containers/0/resources\",\n          \"value\": {\n            \"requests\": {\"cpu\": \"500m\", \"memory\": \"1Gi\"},\n            \"limits\":   {\"cpu\": \"2000m\", \"memory\": \"4Gi\"}\n          }\n        }\n      ]'\n\n      kubectl -n ray rollout status deployment/ray-head\n      kubectl -n ray rollout status deployment/ray-worker\n      ```\n\n      ### 3c. Scale ray-worker to 5 replicas\n\n      ```bash\n      kubectl -n ray scale deployment ray-worker --replicas=5\n      kubectl -n ray rollout status deployment/ray-worker\n      ```\n\n      ### 3d. (Optional) Expose dashboard as NodePort\n\n      ```bash\n      kubectl -n ray patch svc ray-head -p '{\"spec\":{\"type\":\"NodePort\"}}'\n      # Record the assigned node port:\n      kubectl -n ray get svc ray-head -o jsonpath='{.spec.ports[?(@.name==\"dashboard\")].nodePort}'\n      ```\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 4. Rollback Procedure\n\n      If any step introduces instability:\n\n      ```bash\n      # Roll back image change\n      kubectl -n ray rollout undo deployment/ray-head\n      kubectl -n ray rollout undo deployment/ray-worker\n\n      # Restore worker replica count to 3\n      kubectl -n ray scale deployment ray-worker --replicas=3\n\n      # Remove resource limits (revert to empty resources)\n      kubectl -n ray patch deployment ray-head --type=json -p='[\n        {\"op\": \"remove\", \"path\": \"/spec/template/spec/containers/0/resources\"}\n      ]'\n      kubectl -n ray patch deployment ray-worker --type=json -p='[\n        {\"op\": \"remove\", \"path\": \"/spec/template/spec/containers/0/resources\"}\n      ]'\n      ```\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 5. Change Sequencing\n\n      Apply changes in this order during the upgrade window to limit blast radius:\n\n      1. Resource requests/limits (no pod restarts beyond normal rollout)\n      2. Image upgrade (rolling restart, head first, then workers)\n      3. Scale-up (additive, no disruption to existing pods)\n      4. NodePort exposure (optional, requires separate security sign-off)\n\n      Each step should be verified with `kubectl -n ray get pods` and a smoke-test\n      Ray job before proceeding to the next step.\n\n      ---\n\n      *This plan is READ-ONLY. No live resources were modified during its generation.*\n  kind: ConfigMap\n  metadata:\n    creationTimestamp: \"2026-06-24T06:34:09Z\"\n    name: change-plan\n    namespace: ray\n    resourceVersion: \"43783\"\n    uid: 934e16fc-af4b-4b99-8be8-83a403b78597\n- apiVersion: v1\n  data:\n    job.py: |\n      import subprocess\n      import socket\n      import ray\n\n      my_ip = socket.gethostbyname(socket.gethostname())\n\n      subprocess.run([\"ray\", \"stop\", \"--force\"], capture_output=True)\n      subprocess.run(\n          [\"ray\", \"start\", \"--address=ray-head:6379\", \"--node-ip-address=\" + my_ip, \"--num-cpus=0\"],\n          check=True\n      )\n\n      ray.init(address=\"ray-head:6379\", _node_ip_address=my_ip)\n\n      print(\"pong\")\n\n      ray.shutdown()\n      subprocess.run([\"ray\", \"stop\", \"--force\"], capture_output=True)\n  kind: ConfigMap\n  metadata:\n    annotations:\n      kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration: |\n        {\"apiVersion\":\"v1\",\"data\":{\"job.py\":\"import ray\\n\\nray.init(address=\\\"ray://ray-head:10001\\\")\\n\\nprint(\\\"pong\\\")\\n\\nray.shutdown()\\n\"},\"kind\":\"ConfigMap\",\"metadata\":{\"annotations\":{},\"labels\":{\"app.kubernetes.io/component\":\"job-script\",\"app.kubernetes.io/name\":\"ray\",\"bench.ray.cluster\":\"ray\"},\"name\":\"ray-job-script\",\"namespace\":\"ray\"}}\n    creationTimestamp: \"2026-06-24T06:17:43Z\"\n    labels:\n      app.kubernetes.io/component: job-script\n      app.kubernetes.io/name: ray\n      bench.ray.cluster: ray\n    name: ray-job-script\n    namespace: ray\n    resourceVersion: \"43360\"\n    uid: 80e9abae-afb2-4b18-bd5f-a037073be833\nkind: List\nmetadata:\n  resourceVersion: \"\"","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc02510d-bc43-4535-b408-26e796008627","uuid":"e13ba7b7-c231-417f-b5f2-5bf0f057a155","timestamp":"2026-06-24T06:34:40.450Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"apiVersion: v1\nitems:\n- apiVersion: v1\n  data:\n    plan.md: |\n      # Ray Cluster Change/Migration Plan\n      Generated: 2026-06-24\n      Namespace: ray\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 1. Current State\n\n      ### Deployments\n\n      | Resource    | Replicas | Image                  |\n      |-------------|----------|------------------------|\n      | ray-head    | 1        | rayproject/ray:2.9.0   |\n      | ray-worker  | 3        | rayproject/ray:2.9.0   |\n\n      **Non-default configuration already in place (applied prior to this plan):**\n      - ray-worker replica count raised to 3 (default is 1).\n      - ray-head image upgraded to rayproject/ray:2.9.0.\n      - ray-head Service exposes the Ray Dashboard on port 8265 (not present in a vanilla deploy).\n\n      ### Resource Requests / Limits\n\n      Neither ray-head nor ray-worker have any CPU or memory requests or limits defined\n      (`resources: {}`). The head node is configured with `--num-cpus=0` (no task\n      scheduling on head); each worker is configured with `--num-cpus=1`.\n\n      ### ray-head Service\n\n      ```\n      Name:      ray-head\n      Type:      ClusterIP\n      ClusterIP: 10.96.112.176\n      Ports:\n        gcs        6379/TCP   (Ray GCS / node connect endpoint)\n        dashboard  8265/TCP   (Ray Dashboard — exposed, ClusterIP only)\n      ```\n\n      The dashboard port (8265) i